obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `THE INDIAN ANTARCTIC ACT, 2022`
  line `A CT NO. 1 3 OF 202 2`
  line `[ 6 th August, 202 2. ]`
  line `An Act to provide for the national measures for protecting the Antarctic environment and dependent and`
  line `associated ecosystems and to give effect to the Antarctic Treaty, the Convention on the`
  line `Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources and to the Protocol on Environmental`
  line `Protection to the Antarctic Treaty and for matters connected therewith or incidental thereto.`
  line `W HEREAS, the Antarctic Treaty was signed at Washington D.C. on the 1st day of December, 1959;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, the Antarctic Treaty was initially signed by twelve countries and since then`
  line `forty - two other countries have acceded to the Treaty;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, of the total of fifty - four State Parties to the Treaty, twenty - nine countries have the`
  line `status of Consultative Party with a right to vote in the Antarctic Consultative Meetings and twenty - five`
  line `countries are Non - Consultative Parties having no right to vote therein;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, India signed the Antarctic Treaty on the 19th day of August, 1983 and received`
  line `the consultative status on the 12th day of September, 1983;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, the Convention on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources was`
  line `signed at Canberra on the 20th day of May, 1980, inter alia, for the protection and preservation of the`
  line `Antarctic environment and, in particular, for the preservation and conservation of marine living`
  line `resources in Antarctica;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, India ratified the said Convention on the 17th day of June, 1985 and is a member`
  line `of the Commission for Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources under that Convention;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, the Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty was signed at`
  line `Madrid on the 4th day of October, 1991, inter alia, to strengthen the Antarctic Treaty system and for the`
  line `development of a comprehensive regime for the protection of the Antarctic environment and dependent`
  line `and associated ecosystems;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, India signed the Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty on`
  line `the 14th day of January, 1998;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, the Antarctica lies south of 60 ° South Latitude and which is a natural reserve,`
  line `devoted to peace and science and should not become the scene or object of any international discord;`
  line `A ND WHEREAS, it is considered necessary to give effect to the said Treaty, the Convention and the`
  line `Protocol and to make provisions for the protection of the Antarctic environment and dependent and`
  line `associated ecosystems and for the regulation of various activities envisaged in Antarctica and for`
  line `matters connected therewith or incidental thereto.`
  line `B E it enacted by Parliament in the Seventy - third Year of the Republic of India as follows: —`
  line `CHAPTER I`
  line `P RELIMINARY`
  line `1. Short title and commencement. — ( 1 ) This Act may be called the Indian Antarctic Act, 2022.`
  line `( 2 ) It shall come into force on such date 1 as the Central Government may, by notification in the`
  line `Official Gazette, appoint and different dates may be appointed for different provisions of this Act.`
  line `1. 7th August, 2023, vide notification No. S.O. 3509(E), dated 7th August, 2023, see Gazette of India, Extraordinary, Part II,`
  line `sec. 3( ii ).`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-7
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Page 7`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  sourcePage 7
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line 7
  line `2. Application. — This Act shall apply to, —`
  line `( a ) a citizen of India; or`
  line `( b ) a citizen of any other country; or`
  line `( c ) a company, body corporate, corporation, partnership firm, joint venture, an association of`
  line `persons or any other entity incorporated, established or registered as such under any law in force`
  line `in India; or`
  line `( d ) any vessel or aircraft registered in India or outside India,`
  line `if such person, vessel or aircraft is part of an Indian expedition to Antarctica under a permit issued`
  line `under this Act and shall include any such vessel or aircraft which is registered in India but chartered`
  line `by any other Party for entering into Antarctica;`
  line `( e ) Antarctica, comprising of the following areas, namely: —`
  line `( i ) the continent of Antarctica, including its ice - shelves;`
  line `( ii ) all islands south of 60° South Latitude, including their ice - shelves;`
  line `( iii ) all areas of the continental shelf that are adjacent to that continent or to those islands`
  line `that are south of 60° South Latitude;`
  line `( iv ) all sea and air space south of 60 ° South Latitude; and`
  line `( v ) the area specified in Article I of the Convention on the Conservation of Antarctic`
  line `Marine Living Resources.`
  line `3. Definitions. — ( 1 ) In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires, —`
  line `( a ) “ activity ” means any kind of operation in Antarctica, including tourism, research,`
  line `conservation, fishing and commercial fishing;`
  line `( b ) “ aircraft ” shall have the same meaning as assigned to it in clause ( 1 ) of section 2 of the`
  line `Aircraft Act, 1934 (22 of 1934);`
  line `( c ) “ Analyst ” means a person designated as such by the Committee to collect and analyse any`
  line `sample or matter under sub - section ( 2 ) of section 31;`
  line `( d ) “ another Party to the Treaty ” or “ another Party to the Protocol ” means any Party other than`
  line India;
  line `( e ) “ Antarctica ” means the Antarctic area referred to in clause ( e ) of section 2;`
  line `( f ) “ Antarctic environment ” means the ecosystems dependent on and associated with the`
  line `Antarctic environment, the intrinsic value of its wilderness and aesthetics, its value as an area for`
  line `the conduct of scientific research or research that is essential to understand the global`
  line `environment, the climate and the composition of the atmosphere;`
  line `( g ) “ Committee ” means the Committee on Antarctic Governance and Environmental`
  line `Protection established under sub - section ( 1 ) of section 23;`
  line `( h ) “ Comprehensive Environmental Evaluation ” means a comprehensive evaluation of`
  line `environmental impact assessment referred to in sub - section ( 5 ) of section 27;`
  line `( i ) “ Convention ” means the Convention on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living`
  line `Resources signed on the 20th day of May, 1980 in Canberra, Australia;`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-8
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Page 8`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  sourcePage 8
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line 8
  line `( j ) “ Consultative Parties ” means any State Party signatory to the Antarctic Treaty and the`
  line `Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty having voting rights in any decision,`
  line `measures and resolutions adopted by the Antarctica Treaty Consultative Meeting;`
  line `( k ) “ Indian expedition ” means a journey undertaken by any person or persons to the Antarctica`
  line `organised by India;`
  line `( l ) “ Initial Environmental Evaluation ” means a preliminary evaluation of environmental`
  line `impact assessment referred to in sub - section ( 5 ) of section 27;`
  line `( m ) “ land ” includes all islands, continental shelf and any ice - shelf, without prejudice to`
  line `scientific definition of ice - shelf;`
  line `( n ) “ notification ” means a notification published in the Official Gazette and the expressions`
  line `“ notify ” or “ notified ” shall be construed accordingly;`
  line `( o ) “ Operator ”, in relation to a vessel or aircraft, means the owner or the person for the time`
  line `being having the management of that vessel or aircraft;`
  line `( p ) “ Party ” means a State Party signatory to the Antarctic Treaty or a member State of the`
  line `United Nations;`
  line `( q ) “ permit ” means a permit issued by the Committee under section 27;`
  line `( r ) “ person ” means a person or entity referred to in clauses ( a ), ( b ) and ( c ) of section 2;`
  line `( s ) “ prescribed ” means prescribed by rules made under this Act;`
  line `( t ) “ Protocol ” means the Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty signed`
  line `at Madrid on the 4th day of October, 1991, which came into force on the 14th day of`
  line `January, 1998;`
  line `( u ) “ station ” includes any worksites, building or group of buildings or any temporary facility`
  line `in Antarctica;`
  line `( v ) “ Treaty ” means the Antarctic Treaty signed at Washington D.C. on the 1st day of`
  line `December, 1959 which came into force on the 23rd day of June, 1961;`
  line `( w ) “ vessel ” shall have the same meaning as assigned to it in clause ( 55 ) of section 3 of the`
  line `Merchant Shipping Act, 1958 (44 of 1958);`
  line `( x ) “ waste ” means unusable unserviceable movable property, including solid, liquid and`
  line `gaseous matter, which the possessor or generator wants to discharge, or the controlled disposal of`
  line `which is called for in order to preserve public welfare and in particular, the protection of the`
  line `environment; or residual radioactive matter or radioactive components of disassembled or`
  line `dismantled facilities, the controlled disposal of which shall be made in accordance with the`
  line `Atomic Energy Act, 1962 (33 of 1962).`
  line `( 2 ) The words and expressions used herein and not defined but defined in the Treaty or the`
  line `Convention or the Protocol shall have the same meaning as respectively assigned to them in the Treaty`
  line `or the Convention or the Protocol.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-9
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Page 9`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  sourcePage 9
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line 9
  line `CHAPTER II`
  line `R EQUIREMENT AS TO PERMIT`
  line `4. Permit for Indian expedition to Antarctica. — No person in an Indian expedition shall enter`
  line `or remain in Antarctica without a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol:`
  line `Provided that no permit shall be required in the case of a person who is travelling through, on or`
  line `above the high seas, to an immediate destination outside Antarctica.`
  line `5. Permit for Indian station in Antarctica. — No person shall enter or remain in an Indian`
  line `station in Antarctica without a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol.`
  line `6. Permit for vessel and aircraft entering Antarctica. — No vessel or aircraft registered in India`
  line `shall enter or remain in Antarctica without a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the`
  line `Protocol:`
  line `Provided that no permit shall be required in the case of a vessel travelling through, on or above the`
  line `high seas, to an immediate destination outside Antarctica:`
  line `Provided further that no permit shall be required in respect of an aircraft travelling to an`
  line `immediate destination outside Antarctica.`
  line `7. Permit for mineral resource activities. — No person or vessel in Antarctica shall —`
  line `( a ) drill, dredge or excavate for mineral resources;`
  line `( b ) collect any samples of mineral resources; or`
  line `( c ) do anything for the purpose of identifying specific mineral resource occurrences or`
  line `deposits, or areas where such occurrences or deposits may be found,`
  line `except in accordance with a permit issued under this Act:`
  line `Provided that no permit shall be issued for the purposes of this section unless the Committee is`
  line `satisfied that the activities shall be carried on only for the purposes —`
  line `( a ) of scientific research; or`
  line `( b ) connected with the construction, maintenance or repair in Antarctica of an Indian station or`
  line `any other structure, road, runway or jetty maintained by or on behalf of India.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section, “ mineral resource ” means any natural resource`
  line `that is neither living nor renewable.`
  line `8. Permit for certain activities in Antarctica. — No person in Antarctica shall, without a permit`
  line `or written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol —`
  line `( a ) remove or damage native plants intentionally in a manner that significantly affects their`
  line `local distribution or abundance;`
  line `( b ) fly or land a helicopter or other aircraft intentionally in a manner that disturbs any`
  line `concentration of native birds or seals;`
  line `( c ) use a vehicle or vessel, including a hovercraft and a small boat, intentionally in a manner`
  line `that disturbs any concentration of native birds or seals;`
  line `( d ) use an explosive or firearm intentionally in a manner that disturbs any concentration of`
  line `native birds or seals;`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-10
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Page 10`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  sourcePage 10
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line 10
  line `( e ) while on foot, wilfully disturb a breeding or moulting native bird or concentration of seals;`
  line `( f ) significantly damage any concentration of terrestrial native plants by landing an aircraft,`
  line `driving a vehicle or walking on it;`
  line `( g ) engage in any activity that results in the significant adverse change of the habitat of any`
  line `specially protected species or population of native mammals, native birds, native plants or native`
  line invertebrates;
  line `( h ) remove soil or any biological material native to Antarctica intentionally; or`
  line `( i ) kill, injure, capture, handle or molest a native mammal or native bird unless such act was`
  line `done to protect the life of a person.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section, —`
  line `( i ) “ native bird ” means a member, at any stage of its life cycle including eggs, of any species`
  line `of the class Aves that is indigenous to Antarctica or that occurs there seasonally through natural`
  line `migrations including any part, product, egg, or offspring or the dead body or parts thereof and`
  line fossils;
  line `( ii ) “ native invertebrate ” means any terrestrial or aquatic invertebrate, at any stage of its life`
  line `cycle that is indigenous to Antarctica, including any part thereof and fossils;`
  line `( iii ) “ native mammal ” means a member of any species of the class mammalia that is`
  line `indigenous to Antarctica or that occurs there seasonally through natural migrations including any`
  line `part, product, egg, or offspring of or the dead body or parts thereof and fossils;`
  line `( iv ) “ native plant ” means any terrestrial or aquatic vegetation, including bryophytes, lichens,`
  line `fungi and algae, at any stage of its life cycle, including seeds and other propagules, that is`
  line `indigenous to Antarctica or parts of such vegetation, other than fossils;`
  line `( v ) “ specially protected species ” means any native species designated as a specially protected`
  line `species in the Protocol and the Convention.`
  line `9. Permit for introducing non - native animals and plants into Antarctica. — No person, vessel`
  line `or aircraft shall introduce in any part of Antarctica any animal of a species that is not indigenous to`
  line `Antarctica, or any plant that is not a native plant, except in accordance with a permit or the written`
  line `authorisation of another Party to the Protocol:`
  line `Provided that the provisions of this section shall not apply to food other than poultry or live`
  line animals.
  line `10. Permit for introducing microscopic organisms. — No person shall introduce into any part of`
  line `Antarctica any microscopic organism of a species which is not indigenous to Antarctica, except in`
  line `accordance with a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol.`
  line `11. Permit to enter protected areas. — No person or vessel or aircraft shall enter into an`
  line `Antarctic Specially Protected Area or Marine Protected Area as may be prescribed except in`
  line `accordance with a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol.`
  line `12. Permit for waste disposal. — No person, vessel or aircraft shall dispose of waste in Antarctica`
  line `except in accordance with a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol.`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-11
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Page 11`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  sourcePage 11
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line 11
  line `13. Permit for discharge into sea. — No vessel shall, while in Antarctica, discharge into the sea`
  line `any oil or oily mixture, effluent, bilge water or any food waste except in accordance with a permit or`
  line `the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol.`
  line `14. Permit for removal of biological specimen or any other sample from Antarctica. — ( 1 ) The`
  line `Committee may, in individual cases, for reasons to be recorded in writing, grant permit for the`
  line `following purposes, namely: —`
  line `( i ) to obtain specimens or any other sample for study or scientific information;`
  line `( ii ) to obtain specimens for museums, herbariums, zoological and botanical gardens, or other`
  line `educational or cultural institutions or uses:`
  line `Provided that such permission shall be limited so as to ensure that —`
  line `( a ) only such number of native mammals, birds, invertebrates, plants or any other sample are`
  line `taken that are strictly necessary to meet the purposes of this section;`
  line `( b ) only such number of native mammals or birds are killed, such that it can normally be`
  line `replaced by natural reproduction in the following season;`
  line `( c ) the diversity of species, as well as the habitats essential to their existence and the balance`
  line `of the ecological systems existing in the Antarctica are maintained;`
  line `( d ) Ommatophocarossii (Ross Seal) or any other species as may be prescribed shall be`
  line `accorded special protection and permit for killing, injuring, capturing or handling of these species`
  line `may be issued only for scientific purpose, if the survival or recovery of that species or local`
  line `population is not jeopardised, and non - lethal techniques are used as far as possible; and`
  line `( e ) the killing, injuring, capturing or handling of mammals or birds is done in a manner that`
  line `involves least degree of pain and suffering.`
  line `( 2 ) The permit issued for the purposes of this section shall specifically mention the name of the`
  line `issuing authority and the receiver of the permission, the duration and place of the activity permitted`
  line `including the size, weight and volume of the sample intended to be collected.`
  line `15. Certain provisions not to apply during emergencies. — The provisions of sections 4, 5, 6,`
  line `11, 12 and 13 shall not apply in respect of emergencies involving the safety of a person, the protection`
  line `of the environment or the safety of any vessel, aircraft, equipment or facility that has a significant`
  line value.
  line `16. Special permit for commercial fishing in Antarctica. — Any person who intends to go to`
  line `Antarctica for the purpose of commercial fishing shall apply for a permit to the Secretariat of the`
  line `Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources through the Committee.`
  line `CHAPTER III`
  line `P ROHIBITIONS`
  line `17. Prohibition of nuclear explosion or disposal of radioactive waste material in`
  line `Antarctica. — No person shall carry out any nuclear explosion or dispose of any radioactive waste`
  line `material in Antarctica.`
  line `18. Prohibition of introducing non - sterile soil in Antarctica. — No person or vessel shall`
  line `introduce non - sterile soil into any part of Antarctica.`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-12
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Page 12`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  sourcePage 12
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line 12
  line `19. Prohibition of introducing specified substances and products. — No person, vessel or`
  line `aircraft shall introduce into Antarctica any substance or product as may be prescribed.`
  line `20. Prohibition relating to historic sites and monuments. — No person shall damage, destroy or`
  line `remove any historic site or monument or any of its part in Antarctica as may be prescribed.`
  line `21. Prohibition of possessing, selling, etc. — No person or vessel or aircraft while in Antarctica,`
  line `shall possess, sell, offer for sale, trade, give, transport, transfer or send anything that has been obtained`
  line `in contravention of the provisions of this Act.`
  line `22. Prohibition of discharge of certain products or substances. — No vessel shall, while in`
  line `Antarctica, discharge into the sea any garbage, plastic or other product or substance that is harmful to`
  line `the marine environment.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section, garbage, in respect of a vessel, means all kinds of`
  line `victual, domestic and operational waste, excluding fresh fish and parts thereof, generated during the`
  line `normal operation of the ship and liable to be disposed of continuously or periodically.`
  line `CHAPTER IV`
  line `C OMMITTEE ON A NTARCTIC G OVERNANCE AND E NVIRONMENTAL P ROTECTION`
  line `23. Constitution of Committee. — ( 1 ) The Central Government shall, by notification, establish a`
  line `Committee to be called the Committee on Antarctic Governance and Environmental Protection`
  line `consisting of the following members, namely: —`
  line `( a ) Secretary, Ministry of Earth Sciences, Chairperson, ex officio;`
  line `( b ) ten members not below the rank of Joint Secretary, ex officio, to be nominated by the`
  line `Central Government, from any of the Ministries or Departments or organisations of the Central`
  line `Government dealing with, —`
  line `( i ) Defence;`
  line `( ii ) External Affairs;`
  line `( iii ) Finance;`
  line `( iv ) Fisheries;`
  line `( v ) Legal Affairs;`
  line `( vi ) Science and Technology;`
  line `( vii ) Shipping;`
  line `( viii ) Tourism;`
  line `( ix ) Environment;`
  line `( x ) Communication;`
  line `( xi ) Space;`
  line `( xii ) National Centre for Polar and Ocean Research; and`
  line `( xiii ) National Security Council Secretariat;`
  line `( c ) two experts to be nominated by the Central Government, from the fields of, —`
  line `( i ) Antarctic environment; and`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-13
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Page 13`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  sourcePage 13
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line 13
  line `( ii ) Geo - politics;`
  line `( d ) such other experts in the relevant field, to be nominated by the Central Government.`
  line `( 2 ) An officer, not below the rank of Joint Secretary in the Ministry of Earth Sciences, shall be the`
  line `Member - Secretary, ex officio.`
  line `( 3 ) The members nominated under clauses ( c ) and ( d ) of sub - section ( 1 ) shall hold office for such`
  line `period and subject to such terms and conditions as may be specified in the notification referred to in`
  line `sub - section ( 1 ).`
  line `( 4 ) The members nominated under clauses ( c ) and ( d ) of sub - section ( 1 ) shall be entitled to receive`
  line `such allowances or fees as may be prescribed, for attending the meetings of the Committee.`
  line `( 5 ) In the discharge of their functions, the members shall follow such procedure as may be`
  line prescribed.
  line `24. Meetings of Committee. — The Committee shall meet at such intervals and observe such rules`
  line `of procedure in regard to the transaction of business at its meetings (including the quorum thereat) as`
  line `may be prescribed.`
  line `25. Functions of Committee. — The Committee shall perform the following functions, namely: —`
  line `( a ) monitor, implement and ensure compliance of the relevant international laws, emission`
  line `standards and rules for the protection of Antarctic environment by the Operators or by any other`
  line `persons engaged in programmes and activities in Antarctica;`
  line `( b ) undertake any advisory, supervisory or enforcement activities in relation to programmes`
  line `and activities in Antarctica;`
  line `( c ) obtain and review relevant information and reports provided by Parties to the Treaty, the`
  line `Convention, the Protocol and other Parties engaged in programmes and activities in Antarctica;`
  line `( d ) maintain records pertaining to the programmes and activities conducted by Parties in`
  line Antarctica;
  line `( e ) ensure that the programmes and activities are consistent with India's obligations under the`
  line `Treaty, the Convention, the Protocol and with such other relevant law for the time being in force`
  line `in India;`
  line `( f ) determine the terms and conditions of the permit issued under this Act;`
  line `( g ) negotiate fees or charges with other Parties to the Treaty, the Convention and the Protocol`
  line `on a case to case basis in respect of the programmes and activities in Antarctica;`
  line `( h ) collaborate with other Parties to attain the above goals; and`
  line `( i ) such other functions as may be delegated to it by the Central Government.`
  line `26. Power of Central Government to give directions. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may give`
  line `such directions, as it may deem necessary, to the Committee for the effective administration of this`
  line `Act and the Committee shall comply with such directions.`
  line `( 2 ) In case of a dispute between the Committee and the Central Government, the decision of the`
  line `Central Government shall be final.`
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-14
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Page 14`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  sourcePage 14
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line 14
  line `CHAPTER V`
  line `G RANT, SUSPENSION OR CANCELLATION OF PERMIT`
  line `27. Application for permit. — ( 1 ) Every application for grant of permit under this Act shall be`
  line `made to the Committee in accordance with the provisions of this Chapter.`
  line `( 2 ) Every application under sub - section ( 1 ) shall be in such form, contain such particulars and be`
  line `accompanied by such fees as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 3 ) The Committee may, after making such inquiry as it deems fit and having regard to the`
  line `particulars referred to in sub - section ( 4 ) and subject to such terms and conditions as may be`
  line `prescribed, grant permit for the purposes of this Act.`
  line `( 4 ) While granting permit under sub - section ( 3 ), the Committee shall have regard to the following`
  line `matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) adverse effect on climate or weather patterns;`
  line `( b ) adverse effect on air, snow, soil, land or water quality;`
  line `( c ) significant changes in the atmospheric, terrestrial, aquatic, glacial, noise or marine`
  line environment;
  line `( d ) harmful changes in the distribution, abundance or productivity of native microbes, animal`
  line `or plant species or their population;`
  line `( e ) harm or jeopardise endangered species or population;`
  line `( f ) harm or significantly jeopardise the areas of environmental, biological, geological,`
  line `scientific, historic, wilderness or aesthetic significance or of a primeval nature; and`
  line `( g ) such other significant detrimental effects on the Antarctic environment and its dependent`
  line `and associated ecosystems as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 5 ) The Committee shall, before issuing a permit, require the applicant to carry out the`
  line `environmental impact assessment of the proposed activities in such manner as may be prescribed and`
  line `shall issue a permit if the conditions specified therein has been complied with:`
  line `Provided that any application for a permit relating to activities in Antarctica which has reasonable`
  line `apprehension of causing less than a minor or transitory impact on the environment shall be made to the`
  line `Committee six months prior to the commencement of the proposed activity:`
  line `Provided further that while examining an activity, the Committee shall take into account the`
  line `opinion of the independent experts:`
  line `Provided also that if after examination, the Committee is satisfied that such activity has reasonable`
  line `apprehension of causing minor or transitory impact on the environment, then it shall require the`
  line `applicant to conduct an Initial Environmental Evaluation and to submit a report thereon to it, three`
  line `months prior to the commencement of the proposed activity:`
  line `Provided also that if after conducting the Initial Environmental Evaluation, the Committee is of`
  line `the opinion that the activities will have more than a minor or transitory impact on the environment, it`
  line `shall require the applicant to conduct a Comprehensive Environmental Evaluation and to submit a`
  line `report thereon.`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-15
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Page 15`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  sourcePage 15
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line 15
  line `( 6 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in this Act, the Committee shall not grant a permit under`
  line `this section authorising any person or a vessel or an aircraft on an Indian expedition, unless it is`
  line `satisfied that a waste management plan and an emergency plan for the expedition have been prepared`
  line `in such manner as may be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that the waste management plan shall include details of such wastes which are intended`
  line `to be shipped from Antarctica into the Indian territory or territory of any other Party for disposal.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this sub - section, —`
  line `( i ) “ waste management plan ” means the waste management plan referred to in sub - section ( 3 )`
  line `of section 34;`
  line `( ii ) “ emergency plan ” means a plan to meet the environmental emergency referred to in`
  line `section 39.`
  line `( 7 ) The permit granted under this section, unless sooner revoked, shall remain in force for such`
  line `period as specified in the permit and may be renewed, on an application made in this behalf sixty days`
  line `before the date of its expiration, for such period and on payment of such fees as may be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that a permit may be renewed on an application made within sixty days before the date`
  line `of its expiration, if the Committee is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not making the`
  line `application on time.`
  line `28. Liability of owner or Operator in certain cases. — Notwithstanding anything contained in`
  line `any other law for the time being in force, where a vessel or aircraft is part of an Indian expedition or`
  line `fishing in Antarctica but whose owner or Operator is not part of such expedition or fishing, then such`
  line `owner or Operator who is sufficiently identified in the permit, either by class or other description shall`
  line `also be bound by the conditions of the permit.`
  line `29. Suspension or cancellation of permit. — ( 1 ) If the Committee has reasonable grounds to`
  line `believe that the holder of any permit has made any incorrect or false statement or concealed any`
  line `material fact in the application or has contravened any of the provisions of this Act or the rules or`
  line `orders made or notifications issued thereunder or contravened any conditions of permit, it may, by`
  line `order, suspend the permit pending the completion of any inquiry against such permit holder.`
  line `( 2 ) After making an inquiry under sub - section ( 1 ), the Committee may, without prejudice to any`
  line `other penalty to which such permit holder may be liable under the provisions of this Act, cancel the`
  line `permit:`
  line `Provided that no permit shall be suspended under sub - section ( 1 ) or cancelled under this`
  line `sub - section, unless the holder of the permit has been given a reasonable opportunity of being heard:`
  line `Provided further that the Committee may suspend or cancel a permit without giving the permit`
  line `holder an opportunity of being heard, if it is satisfied, for reasons to be recorded in writing, that it is`
  line `not reasonably practicable to do so.`
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub - section ( 1 ) or sub - section ( 2 ), the Central`
  line `Government or the Committee may, in the interest of national security, maintenance of law and order`
  line `or any other matter of public interest and without prejudice to any additional penalty to which such`
  line `permit holder may be liable under the provisions of this Act, order the suspension or cancellation of`
  line `such permit.`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-16
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `Page 16`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  sourcePage 16
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line 16
  line `( 4 ) Any person whose permit has been suspended under sub - section ( 1 ) shall, immediately after`
  line `such suspension, stop all activities in respect of which the permit has been granted, until the order of`
  line `suspension has been revoked.`
  line `( 5 ) Every holder of a permit which is suspended or cancelled shall, immediately after such`
  line `suspension or cancellation, surrender the permit to the Committee.`
  line `( 6 ) Every order of suspension or cancellation of a permit under this section shall be in writing.`
  line `CHAPTER VI`
  line `I NSPECTIONS`
  line `30. Inspection in India. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may designate any officer as an Inspector,`
  line `having such qualifications and experience as may be prescribed, for performing the duties and`
  line `exercising the powers of inspections in India under this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) The Inspector may, for the purposes of this Act —`
  line `( a ) enter and search any place including vessel, container, platform anchored at sea, shipping`
  line `container or conveyance;`
  line `( b ) examine any substance, product or thing;`
  line `( c ) open and examine any receptacle or package, if it contains any doubtful substance, product`
  line `or thing;`
  line `( d ) examine any book, record, data or other documents and make copies or take extracts of the`
  line same;
  line `( e ) take samples of things, if relevant;`
  line `( f ) conduct any test or take any measurement; and`
  line `(g) such other functions as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 3 ) The Inspector may confiscate a sample taken in violation of the permit issued under this Act.`
  line `( 4 ) The owner or person - in - charge of a place being inspected and every person found in the place`
  line `of inspection shall —`
  line `( a ) extend all reasonable assistance to enable the Inspector to carry out his duties under this`
  line `Act; and`
  line `( b ) provide any information which the Inspector may require.`
  line `31. Inspection of international facilities. — ( 1 ) The Committee shall constitute an inspection team`
  line `consisting of such number of observers as it may deem necessary and shall designate one of them as`
  line `the head of the team, for the purposes of carrying out inspections in Antarctica in such manner as may`
  line `be prescribed.`
  line `( 2 ) The Committee may designate any of its officer having such qualifications and experience as`
  line `may be prescribed, to be an Analyst who shall be a part of the inspection team.`
  line `( 3 ) The Analyst shall collect and examine any sample or matter and perform such other duties as`
  line `may be delegated to him by the head of the inspection team.`
  line `( 4 ) The inspections in Antarctica may be carried out jointly with one or more Parties, if deemed`
  line necessary.
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-17
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Page 17`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  sourcePage 17
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line 17
  line `( 5 ) The inspection team may inspect any station after giving prior notice to the Party or Parties`
  line `whose station it proposes to inspect.`
  line `( 6 ) The inspection team may, at any reasonable time, enter any place including vessel, aircraft,`
  line `container, platform anchored at sea, shipping container or conveyance, managed by India in Antarctica`
  line `to which it has reasonable grounds to believe that the provisions of this Act apply:`
  line `Provided that nothing in this sub - section shall apply to such vessel or aircraft which is not part of`
  line `an Indian expedition.`
  line `( 7 ) The inspection team may, at any reasonable time, board or travel in a vessel or an aircraft in`
  line `Antarctica and may carry out inspection of such vessel or aircraft or its communication system after`
  line `giving prior notice to the Party concerned.`
  line `( 8 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in this section, the inspection team shall not inspect any`
  line `station, installation, equipment, platform anchored at sea, shipping container or conveyance that is`
  line `owned by a person who is neither a citizen of India nor a part of Indian expedition unless due notice`
  line `for inspection of the property or installation has been served to the Party who is the owner of such`
  line `property or installation.`
  line `( 9 ) The owner of a place or a person - in - charge of a place being inspected under this Act and every`
  line `person found in the place shall give all reasonable assistance to enable the inspection team to carry out`
  line `its functions under this Act and provide with any information as may be required by it.`
  line `32. Obstruction and false information. — ( 1 ) No person shall obstruct an Inspector or inspection`
  line `team or hinder any of them in performing their functions in India or in Antarctica.`
  line `( 2 ) No person shall knowingly or negligently provide any person false or misleading information,`
  line `results or samples or file a document containing false or misleading information.`
  line `CHAPTER VII`
  line `W ASTE DISPOSAL AND WASTE MANAGEMENT`
  line `33. Waste disposal. — The waste disposal sites on land and abandoned worksites shall be cleaned`
  line `up by the generators of such waste and the users of such sites:`
  line `Provided that the provisions of this section shall not apply if the removal of any structure or waste`
  line `material may result in any adverse environmental impact referred to in sub - section ( 5 ) of section 27`
  line `than leaving the structure or waste material in its existing location.`
  line `34. Establishment of waste classification system and waste management plans. — ( 1 ) The`
  line `Committee shall establish a waste classification system —`
  line `( a ) for recording waste in Antarctica from activities by the persons authorised under`
  line `this Act; and`
  line `( b ) to facilitate studies on the environmental impacts of scientific activities and associated`
  line activities.
  line `( 2 ) For the purposes of sub - section ( 1 ), the waste shall be segregated into the following`
  line `categories, namely: —`
  line `( a ) sewage and domestic liquid waste;`
  line `( b ) other liquid waste such as medical and chemical waste including fuels and lubricants;`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-18
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `Page 18`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  sourcePage 18
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line 18
  line `( c ) solids, including organic waste, to be incinerated;`
  line `( d ) other solid waste;`
  line `( e ) radioactive material; and`
  line `( f ) any other waste as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 3 ) The Committee shall prepare, review annually and update its waste management plans,`
  line `including plans on waste reduction, storage and disposal, specifying for each station, facility, field site,`
  line `field camps, vessel and aircraft —`
  line `( a ) programmes for cleaning up existing waste disposal sites and abandoned worksites;`
  line `( b ) current and planned waste management arrangements;`
  line `( c ) current and planned arrangements for analysing the environmental effects of waste and`
  line `waste management;`
  line `( d ) other measures aimed at minimising the environmental effects of waste and waste`
  line management.
  line `( 4 ) No separate information shall be required for small boats which are part of the operations of`
  line `fixed sites or of vessels.`
  line `( 5 ) The existing management plans for vessels and aircraft shall be taken into account in preparing`
  line `the waste management plans under this section.`
  line `( 6 ) The Committee shall, as far as practicable, prepare an inventory of locations of past activities,`
  line `including traverses, fuel depots, field bases, crashed aircraft or any other accidents and such other`
  line `areas as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 7 ) The waste management plans and reports on their implementation shall be included in the`
  line `annual exchange of information with other Parties to the Treaty.`
  line `( 8 ) The Committee shall appoint or designate a waste management officer for each station, facility`
  line `and worksite who shall monitor the implementation of the waste reduction and disposal plans and`
  line `make proposals for their continued development.`
  line `35. Removal of waste from Antarctica. — ( 1 ) The following waste produced in Antarctica by`
  line `generators of such waste shall be removed from there, namely: —`
  line `( a ) radioactive substances within the meaning of the Atomic Energy Act, 1962 (33 of 1962);`
  line `( b ) all kinds of batteries or components thereof;`
  line `( c ) fuel, both liquid and solid;`
  line `( d ) waste containing harmful levels of heavy metals or acutely toxic or harmful persistent`
  line compounds;
  line `( e ) Polyvinyl chloride, polyurethane, polystyrene foam, rubber, lubricating oils, treated`
  line `timbers and other products which contain additives that may produce harmful emissions, if`
  line incinerated;
  line `( f ) all other plastic waste;`
  line `( g ) fuel drums other than those required for logistics purposes;`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-19
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Page 19`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes
  sourcePage 19
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line 19
  line `( h ) other solid, non - combustible waste including but not restricted to glass and metal scraps;`
  line `( i ) residues of carcasses of imported animals;`
  line `( j ) laboratory culture of microorganisms and plant pathogens;`
  line `( k ) introduced avian products;`
  line `( l ) ash and products of incineration;`
  line `( m ) unserviceable machineries and equipment including electronics; and`
  line `( n ) such other waste as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 2 ) The provisions of sub - section ( 1 ) shall not apply to waste, —`
  line `( a ) if they are incinerated, autoclaved or otherwise treated to be made sterile; or`
  line `( b ) if the removal of such waste shall result in greater adverse environmental impact referred`
  line `to in sub - section ( 5 ) of section 27, than leaving them in their existing locations.`
  line `( 3 ) The domestic waste and other liquid waste shall be treated before removing from Antarctica`
  line `and shall be disposed of on ice - free land areas, sea ice, ice shelves or the grounded ice - sheet and shall`
  line `not be discharged into the lake either directly or indirectly:`
  line `Provided that the standards for effluent discharge shall be such as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 4 ) The provisions of sub - section ( 3 ) shall not apply to substances generated by station located on`
  line `ice shelves or the grounded ice - sheet, provided that such waste are disposed of after treatment in deep`
  line `ice pits which is the only practicable option and such pits are not located on known ice - flow lines`
  line `which terminate at ice - free areas or in areas of high ablation.`
  line `( 5 ) The waste under this section shall be disposed of into the sea subject to a permit issued in that`
  line `regard under section 12.`
  line `( 6 ) The waste generated at field camps shall be removed to supporting stations or vessels for`
  line disposal.
  line `36. Disposal of combustive wastes. — ( 1 ) The combustible waste which are not removed by`
  line `generators of such waste shall be burnt in incinerators to a maximum extent practicable to avoid`
  line `harmful emissions and shall not be burned openly.`
  line `( 2 ) The standards for emission from incineration of waste under sub - section ( 1 ) and from other`
  line `equipment and vehicles shall be such as may be prescribed.`
  line `37. Storage of wastes. — ( 1 ) All waste to be removed from Antarctica, or otherwise disposed of by`
  line `the generators of such waste, shall be segregated, contained, confined and stored in such a way so as to`
  line `prevent their dispersal into the environment.`
  line `( 2 ) The containers and tank - systems holding or used for storing hazardous waste shall be —`
  line `( a ) in good and non - leaking condition;`
  line `( b ) made of or lined with materials which will not react with, and are otherwise compatible`
  line `with, the waste to be stored, so that the ability of the containers to contain such waste is not`
  line impaired;
  line `( c ) stored in a manner that allows access for inspection and response to emergencies; and`
obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-20
  sectionNo (20)
