obj_root_law_sections_27:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-27
  sectionNo (27)
  orderNo 27
  title `Page 27`
  content obj_root_law_sections_27_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes
  sourcePage 27
obj_root_law_sections_27_content:
  string
  line 27
  line `STATEMENT OF OBJECTS AND REASONS`
  line `The Antarctic Treaty was signed on the 1st day of December, 1959 by twelve nations, namely,`
  line `Argentina, Australia, Belgium, Chile, French Republic, Japan, New Zealand, Norway, Union of South`
  line `Africa, USSR, the UK and the US which came into force on the 23rd day of June, 1961, after its`
  line `ratification. The Treaty covers the area south of 60°S latitude. The Treaty's objectives are to`
  line `demilitarise Antarctica, establish it as a zone for peaceful research activities and set aside any disputes`
  line `regarding territorial sovereignty, thereby ensuring international cooperation.`
  line `2. The Convention on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources (CCAMLR) was`
  line `signed at Canberra on the 20th day of May, 1980 to protect and preserve the Antarctic environment`
  line `and, particularly, for the preservation and conservation of marine living resources in Antarctica.`
  line `3. The Protocol on the Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty (Madrid Protocol) was`
  line `signed at Madrid on the 4th day of October, 1991, inter alia, to strengthen the Antarctic Treaty system`
  line `and for the development of a comprehensive regime for the protection of the Antarctic environment`
  line `and dependent and associated ecosystems.`
  line `4. India signed the Antarctic Treaty on the 19th day of August, 1983 and received consultative`
  line `status on the 12th day of September, 1983. India is one of the 29 Consultative Parties to the Antarctic`
  line `Treaty. India ratified the CCAMLR on the 17th day of June, 1985 and signed the Madrid Protocol on`
  line `14th day of January, 1998.`
  line `5. India is also a member of the Council of Managers of National Antarctic Programme`
  line `(COMNAP), Scientific Committee of Antarctica Research (SCAR), and CCAMLR, which shows the`
  line `significant position that India holds among the nations involved in Antarctic research. With an active`
  line `research station Maitri at Schirmacher Hills and a second station Bharati at Larsemann Hills, including`
  line `Himadri station in the Arctic, India now belongs to the elite group of nations with multiple research`
  line `stations within the Polar Regions.`
  line `6. There is growing concern over preserving the pristine Antarctic environment and ocean around`
  line `Antarctica from exploitation of marine living resources and human presence in Antarctica. The`
  line `coordination and management of scientific research in Antarctica is implemented by the National`
  line `Centre for Polar and Ocean Research, Goa, an autonomous research Institute under the Ministry of`
  line `Earth Sciences. India organises regular Antarctic expeditions and many persons from India visit`
  line `Antarctica every year as tourists. In the future, the private ship and aviation industry will also start`
  line `operations and promote tourism and fishing in Antarctica, which needs to be regulated. The continuing`
  line `and growing presence of Indian scientists in Antarctica warrants a domestic legislation on Antarctica`
  line `consistent with its obligations as a member of the Antarctic Treaty. This is also in sync with the`
  line `emergence of India as a global leader on important international fronts.`
  line `7. Accordingly, it is proposed to introduce the Indian Antarctic Bill, 2022 in Parliament. The Bill,`
  line `inter alia, proposes to —`
  line `( a ) prohibit Indian expedition to Antarctica or carrying of certain activities in Antarctica`
  line `without a permit or the written authorisation of another Party to the Protocol;`
  line `( b ) establish a Committee to be called the Committee on Antarctic Governance and`
  line `Environmental Protection which shall perform the functions specified therein;`
  line `( c ) provide for inspection in India by an officer designated by the Central Government as an`
  line `Inspector and to constitute an inspection team to carry out inspections in Antarctica;`
obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_28:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-28
  sectionNo (28)
  orderNo 28
  title `Page 28`
  content obj_root_law_sections_28_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes
  sourcePage 28
obj_root_law_sections_28_content:
  string
  line 28
  line `( d ) provide for penalty for contravention of certain provisions of the Bill;`
  line `( e ) provide for the constitution of the fund to be called the Antarctic fund which shall be`
  line `applied towards the welfare of Antarctic research work and protection of Antarctic environment;`
  line `( f ) provide for Designated Courts and their jurisdiction.`
  line `8. The notes on clauses explain in detail the various provisions contained in the Bill.`
  line `9. The Bill seeks to achieve the above objectives.`
  line `DR. JITENDRA SINGH.`
  line `N EW D ELHI;`
  line `The 25 th March, 2022.`
obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes:
  string
  line
